"We want to send a simple message to all countries: Test, test, test. "

WHO Director General Tan Desai issued a call for enhanced testing in Geneva on March 16. "The most effective way to prevent infection and save lives is to break the chain of transmission. To do that, you have to test and isolate, " he said, "You can't put out a fire blindfolded. You can't stop a pandemic if you don't know who's infected. "

As of 17:00 GMT, 18 July, the total number of confirmed cases of new coronary pneumonia worldwide had reached 198,000, according to the Johns Hopkins University. However, at present, there are still many countries face the "detection difficult" problem.

As of 22:30 GMT, 17 July, more than half of 54 countries in Africa have reported confirmed cases of new coronary pneumonia, bringing the total to 30 countries. As of the weekend, only 36 African countries had the capacity to test for the new coronavirus, and testing laboratories could still be overwhelmed if there were a mass infection in Africa, the Bloomberg L.P. reported Monday.

Developed countries are also "behind the curve" in their detection capabilities. For example, since last week, Switzerland has given priority to testing for people at high risk and with severe symptoms, while people with mild illnesses are advised to stay at home and isolate themselves to relieve pressure on health care facilities and laboratories.

The United States also lags far behind other countries. As of March 16, the CDC and local public health laboratories had tested only about 32,000 samples, according to the latest data published on the CDC's website, the total number of confirmed cases in the United States has exceeded 4,000(nearly 6,500 at 17:00 on the 18th) .

According to the interface news earlier reported that the United States testing "slow" , mainly due to harsh conditions, lack of tools. Only about 125 out of every 1 million people in the United States are tested, far fewer than in other countries where the data are published, The New York Times reported Thursday. As of the end of last week, testing in the United States was done manually, with labs able to perform only 40 to 60 tests a day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The number of people tested per 1 million population, from bottom to top: South Korea, Italy, Australia, Austria, the United Kingdom, the Czech Republic, Greece, the United States. Source: New York Times

Unlike in the US, tests have been carried out in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. Since the early days of the outbreak, requiring anyone who has come into contact with a confirmed patient, symptomatic or otherwise, to be tested, this partly explains why the number of confirmed cases in Italy has grown so rapidly.

More than 10,000 tests were completed in Italy at the end of February, when just over 500 people were diagnosed. In some small towns across the country, large-scale testing has also helped cut the transmission chain. In Vaux, near Venice, the local government tested the entire population, some 3,300 people, in late February and isolated 3 per cent of them with or without symptoms. A second round of tests 10 days later showed the infection rate had dropped to 0.3 per cent.

And overseas, the virus detection of the largest country is undoubtedly South Korea. As of midnight on the 18th, a total of 8413 cases of new pneumonia had been confirmed in South Korea, and the number of new cases in four consecutive days was less than 100. Although sporadic clusters of infections remain, South Korea is the only overseas country with more than 1,000 confirmed cases showing a significant slowdown.

Since the first kit was approved on February 4, South Korea has tested 270,000 people for the virus, or one in 200. A total of 633 screening sites have been set up in South Korea, including "drive-in" screening clinics and temporary clinics set up in front of buildings with a daily capacity of 20,000 people, The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday.

In South Korea, tests are free of charge as long as there is a history of exposure or a doctor's recommendation, and the sample takes only 10 minutes to complete. After that, the samples are stored in sealed containers at 40 degrees Fahrenheit and sent to 118 laboratories for analysis by about 1,200 medical professionals, typically in six hours, patients are usually informed of the results within a day.

South Korea's ability to do so draws lessons from the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) of 2015. In recent years, South Korea has introduced an emergency licensing system that has shortened the time it takes for drugs and reagents to reach the market. In addition, the emergency system has been redesigned and RT-PCR detection devices have been installed in major hospitals and local health clinics, providing a basis for rapid diagnosis.

Now South Korean companies with spare power are supplying test kits to other countries. A total of four South Korean companies, including Seegene, a maker of nucleic acid test kits, have been granted emergency use licenses for the new coronavirus kits by the Food and Drug Safety Agency, the company had received "urgent order requests" from more than 30 countries earlier this month.

With 200,000 new cases of pneumonia on the global docket, countries must accelerate the pace of detection. World Health Organization has shipped nearly 1.5 million kits to 120 countries and is working with companies to increase production for those most in need, he said Monday.

Fourteen test kits developed by Chinese universities have also entered the EU market, supplying to Italy, the UK, the Netherlands and 11 other countries. China has previously donated tens of thousands of test kits to Iran, Japan, Pakistan, the African Union, Serbia, the Philippines and other countries and national organizations.
